notes: Although Isissenetnephtys is labeled with the filiation s#=f: his son, it is likely to be a female due to the female name classifier as well as to the fact that two female deities appear as name elements. Nevertheless, the composition of the name is very distinctive that does not seem to be documented elsewhere.

name: o#-m.jj
notes: A. Erman reads the name as  o#-mo.jj (see: Erman, in: ZÄS 33, 19) G. Roeder reads it o#-m-M17?-17? (See: Roeder, Ägyptische Inschriften II, 179–180). This could possibly translated as \
. Ranke probably felt that this was too uncertain and therefore omitted the name in his collection. Names with imperative, however, do exist, although rarely, see PN II, 40.

name: B#k(.t)PtH
notes: It cannot be stated with certainty whether B#k(.t)-PtH is a male (RPN I 91.6) or a female (RPN I 92.14) person. Due to the filiation s#=f: his son and the fact that the female t-ending of the name is not written, it is more likely to assume a male person. The name classifier, as well as the fact that the name behind it is also introduced with S#=f, but is rather to be addressed as a female personal name, could also point to a daughter of stela owner. In this case the female t-ending would have been omitted as it is regularly the case (RPN 92.14)
